---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
const pageDescription = "High-level methodology behind Scouting Grade's 2026 NFL Draft model: what data types are considered and how to interpret outputs.";
const collectionSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "CollectionPage",
  name: "NFL Draft Methodology",
  url: "https://scoutinggrade.com/nfl-draft-methodology",
  description: pageDescription,
  isPartOf: {
    "@type": "WebSite",
    name: "Scouting Grade",
    url: "https://scoutinggrade.com"
  }
};
---
<BaseLayout title="NFL Draft Methodology | Scouting Grade" description={pageDescription} collectionSchema={collectionSchema}>
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>How We Evaluate Prospects</h1>
    <p>Public high-level framework for reading the board, grades, and mock outputs.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="card page-intro">
    <h2 class="section-title">Methodology Overview</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      This page explains how to read Scouting Grade’s board, mock outputs, and scouting cards without exposing the underlying formula. It is
      designed to show what types of evidence matter most and how those signals are translated into the public draft tools.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card methodology-grid">
    <article class="card">
      <h2 class="method-heading">1) Evidence Categories</h2>
      <p class="muted method-copy">
        We review multiple evidence buckets: college production context, athletic markers, role/trait translation signals,
        and external market context.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <h2 class="method-heading">2) Grade vs Rank</h2>
      <p class="muted method-copy">
        <strong>Grade</strong> is player-quality signal. <strong>Rank</strong> is ordering after additional context checks.
        That means two players with close grades can still sort differently.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <h2 class="method-heading">3) Mock Logic Philosophy</h2>
      <p class="muted method-copy">
        Mock outputs balance board value with team context and positional economics. We aim for realistic team classes while still
        allowing variance and upside outcomes.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <h2 class="method-heading">4) Update Cadence</h2>
      <p class="muted method-copy">
        Public pages are refreshed in cycles as new data and news are incorporated. Check the weekly updates page for timestamps.
      </p>
    </article>

  </section>

  <section class="card related-links">
    <h2 class="section-title">Related Draft Tools</h2>
    <div class="related-links-grid">
      <a class="related-link" href="/2026-nfl-draft-big-board">
        <strong>Big Board</strong>
        <span class="muted">See how the public framework translates into the current ranking stack.</span>
      </a>
      <a class="related-link" href="/2026-nfl-player-comparison">
        <strong>Player Compare</strong>
        <span class="muted">Use the translation profile and comp context next to the methodology page.</span>
      </a>
      <a class="related-link" href="/2026-nfl-draft-weekly-updates">
        <strong>Weekly Updates</strong>
        <span class="muted">Track when methodology-driven public refreshes go live on the site.</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    .methodology-grid {
      display: grid;
      gap: .8rem;
    }
    .method-heading {
      margin: 0 0 .4rem;
    }
    .method-copy {
      margin: .2rem 0;
      line-height: 1.55;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
